<h2 id="ALLCAPS">7.8 - EVERYTHING I TYPE AT THE LOGIN PROMPT IS IN CAPS!</H2>

This is a feature, not a bug, actually.

<p>
Virtually all Unix commands and user names are entered using all lowercase.
However, some very old terminals were only capable of uppercase characters,
making them difficult, if not impossible, to use with Unix.
As a workaround, if you entered your user name in all uppercase,
<a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=getty">getty(8)</a>
would assume your terminal was "lowercase challenged" and simply
interpret everything you type as lowercase, while echoing it as uppercase.
If you have a mixed-case or uppercase password, this will make logging in
impossible.

<p>
Hitting CTRL-D at the login prompt will cause getty(8) to terminate, and
<a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=init">init(8)</a>
will relaunch a new one, which will accept uppercase and lowercase
properly.

