<small>$OpenBSD: faq7.html,v 1.60 2004/05/22 03:22:33 nick Exp $</small>
@


1.60
log
@
add 7.9 - EVERYTHING I TYPE AT THE LOGIN PROMPT IS IN CAPS!
Inspired by a problem I've repeatedly had, and a simple and elegant
solution from Dale Rahn.  Fact-check, drahn@@
@
text
@d517 5
a521 6
Virtually all Unix commands and user names are entered using all lower
case.
However, some very old terminals were only capable of upper case only,
making them difficult, if not impossible, to use with Unix.
As a workaround, if you entered your user name in all upper
case,
d523 4
a526 4
would assume your terminal was "lower-case challenged", and simply
interpret everything you type as lower case, while echoing it as upper
case.
If you have a mixed-case or upper-case password, this will make login
d532 2
a533 1
will relaunch a new one, which will accept upper and lower case properly.
d547 1
a547 1
